{"/service/ndnp/tu/batch_tu_kathy_ver01/data/sn89058321/00415621425/1907110801/1021.xml":{"full_text":"the comi USUAL\nMARSHALL 4 BAIRD, Editor aud Publisher\nF.tiUwt at the post offlne at Union City, Ten\no a Beoona-cisM mill iniutr.\nONE DOLUR A YEAH\nTELEPHONE 103\nFRIDAY, NOVEMBER 8, 1907\nANNOUNCEMENTS.\nFLOATER.\nO. B. Jl'DADB.\nVe are authorized to announce O\nR. McDade as a candidate for Floater\nto recresent Dyer. Lake and Obion\nCounties at the next session of the\nTennessee General Assembly.\nFOR THE LEGISLATURE.\nE. N. MOORE.\nWa am mit.hnri7rt ti nnnniinr.ft\nN. Moore as a candidate to represcn\nunion county at tue next eiuu\nthe General Assembly of the State\nTennessee, subject to the action\nthe Democratic party.\nE\nof\nof\nof\nFOR TSUSTEE.\n8. B. BIlATTON.\nBratton a candidate for Trustee of\nObion County, subject to the action\nof the Democratic party.\nG, W. WORLET.\nWe are authorized to announce G\nW. Worle? a candidate for Trustee of\nObion County, subject to the action\nof the Democratic party.\nI. H. SANDERS.\nWa are authorized to announce J. II\nSanders a, candidate for Trustee of\nObion County, subject to the action of\ntne Democratic party.\nFOR SHERIFF.\nR. N. TANKKR8LEY.\nWe are authorized to announce R\nN. Tankersley a candidate for Sheriff\nof Obion County, subject to the action\nor the Democratic party.\nT. J. EA8TERWOOD.\nWe are authorized to announce T.J\nEasterwood as a candidate for Sheriff\nof Obion County, subject to the ac\ntion of the Democratic party.\nT. r. NOAH.\nWe are authorized to announce Tom\nP. Noah as a candidate for Sheriff of\nObion County, subject to the action\nor tue Democratic party.\nA GUT WALKER.\nWe are authorized to announce Guy\nWalker a candidate for Sheriff of\nObion County, subject to the action of\nthe Democratic party; election N ov. 30.\nFOR TAX ASSESSOR.\nTAX ASSESSOR.\nWe are authorized to announce\nLuther Parks as a candidate for Tax\nAssessor of Obion County, subject to\nthe action of the Democratic party.\nElection Nov. 30, 1907.\nH. C. WOODS.\nWe are authorized to announce II.\nC. Woods, of Number Five, a candi\ndate for Tax Assessor of Obion Coun\nty, subject to the Democratic primary\nNovember 30, iwj.\nFOR MAYOR.\nDR. T. D. EDWARDS.\n\"We are authorized to announce Dr.\nTV n. Ed wards as a candidate for\nMayor of Union City. Election first\nSaturday in January, iaus.\nW. H. GARDNER.\nWe are authorized to announce W\nII. Gardner as a candidate for Mayor\nof Union City. Election Jan. 4, iuos\nFOR ALDERMAN.\n8. 8. ALEXANDER.\nWe 'are authorized to announce S. S.\nAlexander a candidate for Alderman\nof Union City. Election Jan. 4, 1908.\nJOHN ADAMS.\nWe are authorized to announce John\nAdams a candidate for Alderman of\nUnion City. Election Jan. 4, 1903.\n3. F. GREGORT.\nWe are authorized to announce J.\nF. Gregory a candidate for Alderman\nof Union City. Election Jan. 4, 1908.\n8. n STONE.\nWe are authorized to announce S.\nH. Stone a candidate for Alderman of\nUnion City. Election Jan. 4, 1908.\n3. d. BTRD1CK.\nWe are authorized to announce J.\nC. Burdlck a candidate for Alderman\nof Union City. Election Jan. 4. 1908.\nK. M. WHIPPLE.\nWe are authorized to announce R.\nM. Whipple a candidate for Alderman\nof Union City. Election Jan. 4,1908.\n17. MOORE.\nEsquire N. Moore announces\nin this week's issue of The Com\nmercial as a candidate for Repre\nsentative of Obion County in the\nTennessee General Assembly. Mr.\nMooro announced in the last cam\npaign, but was prevented from\nmaking the race on account ot\nsickness in his family. He there\nfore withdrew. This year he de\nclares himself a candidate again.\nEsquire E. N. Moore is one of\nObion County's well known, sub\nstantial, reliable citizens, who\ncommands and merits the confi\ndence and esteem of his fellow\ncitizens, He is ambitious in his\nprivate atiairs, having accumu\nlated, by thrift and good judg\nment, a reasonable tsbare of the\ncomforts of home and surround\nings. He is also an honorable\nmember of the Obion County\nCourt, a worthy Christian gentle\nman, fraternal in his associations\nand a veteran of the Civil War with\na splendid record. Withal Mr.\nMoore desires your suffrage as a\nDemocrat, subject to the action o\nthe party, and if elected will do\nall he can for the benefit and up\nbuildinj? of nis home countv. as\nwell a3 for the State at large. W\ntake pleasure in presenting the\nname of Mr. Moore to the voters\nfor their consideration.\nOUR FINANCES SOLID.\nAs solid as the everlasting rocks\nof Gibraltar are the finances of Obi\non County banks. These remarks\nare made advisedly. If by the re\nniotest possible accident New\nYork banks should sink every\ndollar of exchange onr banks have\non deposit there and the rest o\nthe financial world should follow\nto the brink of ruin. Union Citv\nbanks would stand invulnerable to\nevery attack made upon their faith\nand credit.\ne had occasion this week to\nconfer with every bank President\nin Union City.. We have also\nwell authenticated information\nconcerning tneir individual re\nsources. The books of the three\nbanking houses will show that\nthere are tangible net resources\ncovering three-fourths of the en\ntire deposits of these banks, every\ndollar of which is subject to the\ndepositors claims.\nBut while all these things are\ntrue the action of the banks last\nweek was deemed advisable in or\nder to prevent an injudicious and\ninconsiderate attack upon them.\nBut this action wa9 not taken\neven until ue banks everywhere\nelse had done so. There was re\nally no necessity for it in Union\nCity, nor in the county, but since\nit has been done conservative men\nand hundreds of them all over the\ncounty have approved the move\nment.;\nIn 1893 the banks here weath\nered the gale without the slightest\ninjury. To-day they are many\ntimes stronger and safer than dur\ning that panic. Stocks and eecu\nrities were lower then than they\nare now, or have been since that\ntime.\nThere are a few instances where\nthe railroads and industrials are\nower now, but the general aver\nage is higher as the following\nbrief table will show.\nSTOCKS.\n1907 1898\nAmerican Sugar....\nUnited Suites hteel\nAtchison Ry\nC. M. St. Vaul Ky\n&O. Ry\nMissouri Pacific Ry..\nM. K. T. Ry\nNew York Central R. R\nPennsylvania R. R\nSouthern Pacific Ry......\nU. t N. Ry...\nC. R. R\nJnion Pacific Ry.\nN. P. Ry\nReadme Ry\nCol. Fuel Iron\n100\n83\n84\nldl\n28\n52\n24\n96\n1($\n67\n95\n121\nH9\nm\n75\n46\n120\n67\n55\n113\n25\n35\n3(1\n120\n127\n30'\n73\n106\n66\n68\n46\n34\nThe above was at a period when\nthe panic of 19C3 was subsiding.\ntherefore the prices must have\nbeen lower than those which are\nquoted above.\nBut returning to our local banks.\nthe presidents are each amply\nable, and more, to protect every\ndollar of deposits in their respect\nive banks and they are willing to\nunderwrite these liabilities at any\nime necessary. One of these\ngentlemen confided to us the fact\nthat he is worth more than the\nentire deposits of his bank, and\nthat he would at any time secure\nany depositor wholly and entirely\nsatisfactory. The other nreei-\ndents are practically enjoying the\nsame character of financial stand\ningand also vouchsafe that they\nwill in a like manner secure anv\n4\nlability their banks may have.\nWe have these facta from, re-\niable authority, and thus it is to\nbe seen how the banks of the citv\nand county are prepared for a fi\nnancial crisis. One of the pood\n'eatures growing out of the situ\nation is that our people are accept\ning the situation philosophically.\nThey seem to understand that we\nare in co danger of a crisis not at\nthe present status of affairs and\nthat Obion County is, like she has\nalways been, above hieh water\nmark, financially speaking. It is\nto the good judgment of these\npeople that the bankers feel like\nreturning profoundent thanks.\nThe people of Obion County are\nextraordinary intelligent in the\nconduct of their business affairs.\nTHE ONLY WAY.\nThe banks of Union City and\nBank of Troy have issued clearing\nhouse certificates to the amount of\n825,000 to be used in 'lieu of cur\nrency and bank notes. The presi\ndent of each of these banks has\nsigned these certificates as securi\nties, viz: L. S. Parks, John T.\nWalker, K. P. Whitesell, John\nW. Bennett. These notes, and\nothers which may hereafter be is\nsued, are to be used as money and\nare redeemable in currency and\nbank notes, or collateral sufficient\nto cover the face value of the\nnotes. They are' of par value in\nexchange for produce, goods,\nmerchandise and acceptable for\ndeposit on account.\nThe certificates were issued to\nrelieve the scarcity of currency.\nIf the Government is going to\nlend itself to the practice of fur\nnishing money to banks who spec\nulate on margins, Obion County\nfinanciers are going to take care\nof themselves, irrespectively of\nUncle Sam. Hereafter if Con\ngress doesn't pass some measure\nrevoking the privileges of banks\nwhich buy and sell futures on\nchange then we shall always fear\nthe coming of a panic. If a great\nmajority of legislators were not\nspeculators themselves (dealers in\nfutures) a law of this kind would\nhave been in force years ago.\nSomething of this kind must be\ndone.- If not the people will de\nmand it, and the demand will be\nmade in such a way that there will\nbe no doubt about it. Come on,\ngentlemen; get on the square\nThat's the right way and the only\nway. yi\nBEST WE CAN DO.\nIn a certain instance the Nash\nville Tennessean is very liberal in\nits compliments. At the same\ntime we cannot curb an overween\ning desire to manifest our appre\nnation of its kindness. Like\nmany others we are only human.\nHere is the way the extract reads:\n\"One of the best printed and edited\nweeklies of theTcnnessean's exchange\nlist is the Union City Commercial,\nEditors Marshall and Baird carrying\na heavy run of paying advertisements,\nwell balanced by as good news col\numns as are to be found.\"\nave Ybu Tried\nli your g'rocer for it.\nNONE BETTER\nahnke-Walfcer .Milling Co.\nDR. PAUL b. JOYPibR,\nDENTIST\nOrtlce over AVea Drug Co.'s store.\nOfSice Phone 283\nResidence Phone 346\nDR. F. W. WHITEHURST\nDENTIST. x\nOffice: Church street, over Harrison\nElectrical Co.\nPhone 3GO Union City, Tenn.\"\nReelfoot Catch\nRed Fish, Red Snapper,\nSpanish Mackerel, Reelfoot\nLake Fish of all kinds at\nJ. C. BURDICK'S.\nPHONE NO. 3.\nAsk us for prices when selling your grain.\nto\nOUR EXCHANGES.\nWhen the flurry is over you may\nhave cause to congratulate yourself\nthat a curb had been put on your ex\ntravagance. Maury Democrat.\nNotwithstanding the financial panic\nof the North the South is suffering\nbut little as a result and feels very\nwell, thank you. Carroll County Dem\nocrat.\nNew York banks, and banks of other\ncities, may fail or suspend their busi\nness, but the local banks continue to\ndo business as heretofore, and there is\nno cause for alarm or uneasiness. Sa\nvannah Courier.\nWall Street had a flurry the other\nday and hundreds of gallons of water\nwere spilt. But the country goes se\nrenely on unmindful of the fate of the\nworthless gamblers whose grip on the\nprosperity of the land Is day by day\nslipping. Lebanon Banner.\nSuppose now that the stock exchange\nand the board of trade were closed for\n3C5daysln the year? If it helps to\nrestore confidence to close them up a\nfew days, would it not be well to make\nIt permanent. There is where finan\ncial disturbances originate. Para-\ngould Democrat.\nThe financial panic that dawoed\nupon New York City last week, as a\nresult of reckless speculation la about\nto pass over, and normal conditions\nare returning with increased confi\ndence la the banking Institutions of\nthe country. Not a single bank In\nthe South felt the flurry, which is an\nother evidence of the fact that the\nSouth is not as much dependent on\nthe East as formerly for money to\nmove the crops of this section. Dy-\nersburg Gazette.\nSwellest line of hand painted par\nlor table at Bell Furniture Co.\ntiff\ntor\nto\nMl\nto\nto\nto\nto\nto\nto\nto\nGon\nWilliams\nGROCERIES and\nCITY MARKETS\nCountry Produce, Fruits, Cigars, Etc.\nSole agents for Chase Sanborn's\nFamous Boston Teas and Coffees.\nFerndell Pu'.-e Food Products. We\nare sole agents for Bulte's Excel\nlence Flour, the finest the market\naffords.\n...TWO STORES...\nCor. Home College\nPhoni 96\n305 Main Street\nPhones 79 and 516\nS9\nft\nGET THE BEST\nALWAYS CHEAPEST\nALWAYS GOOD\nUNION CITY ICE AND COAL CO.\nDISTRIBUTORS OF COMFORT.\nSaTelephone No. 150.\n5\nK. KIMBE.RLIN,\nLIFE and TORNADO INSURANCE\n5\n5\nt\nt\n2\n4\nPhone Office, 303; Residence, 92.\nit\nit\nGEORGE B. WILLIS, Manager\nWEST TENNESSEE MONUMENT GO.\nDEALERS IN\nAmerican and Foreign Marble and Granifa Monuments\nGet our prices on all kinds of Cemetery Goods, Curbing,\nBuilding Stone, &c. All work finished ir Tit-class style.\nWest cf Sssc22S Scss' Fcssdnr. V IWCJ CITY TEM.\nDr. E. Abram Gulled ge\nResident Physician mi Serpen\nvir. to (tntwince to the public tu and iiuuuj\nI'nion City that he U here for the practice of med\nicine, and taken this medium by which to ac\nquaint you with the fart. All call promptly at\ntended, day or nitiht. Will Rtate for the benefit\nof the poor people that I treat them free of any\ncharge on Monday at my office. Cnnea coininir\nunder my care will receive every necessary at\ntention. Have a large laboratory at tuy com\nmand with the best and purest of drum.\nOFFICE AT McMICHAKL DRUO CO.\nPhone No. 223. VNION CITY. TENN.\nF. and A. M.\nUnion City Lodge No. 531, F. and\nA. M., meets on the first Friday night\nin eacli month at the lodge room In\nthe C. B. A. building. The presence\nof all members Is earnestly requested.\nVisiting members always welcome.\nT. E. Marshall, W. M.\n11. F. Batts, Sec.\nINSOLVENT NOTICE.\nHaving suggested the Insolvency of\nthe estate of J. E. llogan, deceased,\nto the County Court Cleric of Obion\nCounty, Tenn., all persons having\nclaims against said estate are hereby\nuntitled to file them, duly authenti\ncated, with the County Court Clerk of\nObion County, on or before the \"tli\ndayof January, 1908, or the same will\nbe forever barred, both In law aqa\nequity.\nThis, 7th day of October, 1907.\nE. C. Jackson, Administrator.\nUNION CITY.\n(Effective April J4, 1907.)\nBOUTH-BOUNb.\n4.35 p.ni\n4.04 a.m\n4.09 a.m\na.m\nNo. 1, lv Union City\nNo. 3, (Havana Limited)...\nNo, 6, lv Union City\nNo. 15, leaves (week days)...\nNORTH-BOUND.\nNo. 2, lv Union City 11.40 a.m\nNo. 4. (Havana Limited!... 12.24 a.m\nNo. 8, 1 v Union City 2.15 a.m\nNo. 12, leaves (week days). p.m\nOnly the handsomest of Pullman\nLibrary Observation Sleeping Cars,\nwide Vest! bu led Coaches and Dining\nCars, with Electric Lights and Fans,\nare used In the Limited. For all in\nformation call on your Home Agent,\n.r write J no. M. liean, ueneral ras\nsenger Agent, St. Louis.\nR. J. BAKNETT, Agent.\nr.V. Taylor, Jno. m. biall,\nGumI Mmnaecr, (jaml lfMKr Afvnt,\nMOBILE, ALA. IT. LOV1. MO\naw. TTwT i\nji-wviswvmo STATION\nCAIS0\nUlOlAN\nk-\nm m v.\n1 noaiuSaj\nMONTGOMERY\"\nJACaSONVtag\nTIME OF TRAINS AT\nC& St. L. TIME TABLE.\nEAST BOUND.\nNo. 55, ar Union City\nNo. 3,\n1o. 53,\nWEST BOUND.\nNo. 62, ar Union City\nNo. 4,\nNo. 64, M\n7.44 a.m.\n3.0ft p.m.\n11.15 p.iui\n6.44 a.m.\n12.46 p.mi\n7.52 p.m.\nIllinois Central\nRAILROAD.\nSOUTHBOUND.\nNo. 1, Faducah Junction.... 8.0fi p.m\nNo. 3, 6.37 a.m\nNo. ins, 5.13 a.a\nNo. 105, M 3.49 p.m\nNo. 133, 5.61 a.m\nTrain Mo. ins and 13S ar accommodation\nnl atop At Padar-ab Jnnctloa to racoiv or di\nekarc paweoger.\nNORTHBOUND.\nNo. 2, Paducah Junction.... 9.45 a.tu\nNo. 4, ....12.15 a.m\nNo. 104, ....12.05 a.m\nNo. W, 12.10 p.m\nNo. 134, .10p.m\nTrain Va. IM and lo ar Accommodation.\nTicket anl particular a to ipeHte rst.\nlimit, ao l train tuna of yoor bom. Ucwt a(ti t\ntt. uwuu, raaacan aacuuu.\nT. W. HAELOW, j. r. A., roBlTlll.\nX.J. McDOUO ALL. D. P. A.. Pi Orla\nf A.. 0